\b\fs44 How the Internet works?\b0\par
\fs24 Physically, the Internet uses a portion of the total resources of the currently existing public telecommunication networks. Technically, what distinguishes the Internet is its use of a set of protocols called \par
Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol (TCP/IP). Two recent adaptations of Internet technology, the Intranet and the extranet, also make use of the TCP/IP protocol.\par
\par
The Internet can be seen as having two major components:Network protocols and Hardware.\par
\par
\b The protocols\b0 , such as the TCP/IP suite, present sets of rules that devices must follow in order to complete tasks. Without this common collection of rules, machines would not be able to communicate.\par
The protocols are also responsible for translating the alphabetic text of a message into electronic signals that can be transmitted over the Internet, and then back again into legible, alphabetic text.\par
\par
\b Hardware\b0 , the second major component of the Internet, includes everything from the computer or smartphone that is used to access the Internet to the cables that carry information from one device to\par
 another. Additional types of hardware include satellites, radios, cell phone towers, routers and servers.\par
\par
