\b\fs44 WWW:\par
\b0\fs24 World Wide Web, which is also known as a Web, is a collection of websites or web pages stored in web servers and connected to local computers through the internet. These websites contain text pages,\par
digital images, audios, videos, etc. Users can access the content of these sites from any part of the world over the internet using their devices such as computers, laptops, cell phones, etc. The WWW, \par
along with internet, enables the retrieval and display of text and media to your device.\par
\par
The building blocks of the Web are web pages which are formatted in HTML and connected by links called "hypertext" or hyperlinks and accessed by HTTP. These links are electronic connections that link\par
 related pieces of information so that users can access the desired information quickly. Hypertext offers the advantage to select a word or phrase from text and thus to access other pages that provide \par
additional information related to that word or phrase.\par
\par
A web page is given an online address called a Uniform Resource Locator (URL). A particular collection of web pages that belong to a specific URL is called a website, e.g., {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK www.facebook.com }}{\fldrslt{www.facebook.com\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs24 ,\par
 {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK www.google.com }}{\fldrslt{www.google.com\ul0\cf0}}}}\f0\fs24 , etc. So, the World Wide Web is like a huge electronic book whose pages are stored on multiple servers across the world.\par
